  "introduction": "**The Mystery Powder Challenge**:\n*Teacher holds up two white powders (e.g., Sugar and Salt).*\n'Look at these. They both look identical, right? If I give you a spoonful of each, how do we know which is sugar without tasting it?'\n\n*Hook Question*: 'In chemistry, appearance can be deceiving. How do we scientifically prove what something IS, and more importantly, HOW PRECISELY have we measured it?' \nToday, we unlock the language of Chemistry: Classifying Matter and Mastering Measurements."
  ,
  "theory": {
    "overview": "Chemistry begins with understanding matter. We categorize matter into pure substances (elements/compounds) which have fixed properties, and mixtures where components retain their identity. Furthermore, all chemical data comes from measurements. The precision of these measurements is communicated through Significant Figures.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Matter is classified as Pure Substances or Mixtures.",
      "Elements are the simplest form; Compounds have fixed ratios.",
      "Mixtures can be homogeneous (uniform) or heterogeneous (non-uniform).",
      "Significant figures represent the precision of a measurement."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "**1. Classification of Matter**:\n- **Pure Substances**: Have constant composition and distinct properties.\n  - *Elements*: Made of one type of atom (e.g., Cu, O2). Cannot be decomposed chemically.\n  - *Compounds*: Two or more elements combined in fixed mass ratio (e.g., NaCl is always 39.3% Na and 60.7% Cl by mass).\n- **Mixtures**: Physical blend of two or more substances.\n  - *Homogeneous*: Uniform composition, single phase (e.g., Sugar solution).\n  - *Heterogeneous*: Non-uniform, visible boundaries (e.g., Oil and water).\n\n**2. Measurements & Significant Figures**:\n- **SI Units**: The International System of Units used globally.\n  - Mass: Kilogram (kg) or Gram (g).\n  - Length: Meter (m).\n- **Significant Figures **(Sig Figs)\nThe digits that carry meaning contributing to its measurement resolution. \n*Rules Recap*:\n1. Non-zeroes are always significant.\n2. Zeros between non-zeros are significant.\n3. Leading zeros are NOT significant.\n4. Trailing zeros in a number with a decimal point ARE significant.\n5. In calculations, the result must be rounded to match the least precise measurement used."
  },
